text.paragraph:
ZETIA given concomitantly with a statin is contraindicated in patients with active liver disease or unexplained persistent elevations of hepatic transaminase levels [see Contraindications (4)
                           ; 
                              Warnings and Precautions (5.2), and Clinical Pharmacology (12.3)].

In two multicenter, double-blind, placebo-controlled, 12-week studies in 1719 patients with primary hyperlipidemia, ZETIA significantly lowered total-C, LDL-C, Apo B, and TG, and increased HDL-C compared to placebo (see 
                                   Table 6
                                ). Reduction in LDL-C was consistent across age, sex, and baseline LDL-C.

ZETIA, added to on-going statin therapy, significantly lowered total-C, LDL-C, Apo B, and TG, and increased HDL-C compared with a statin administered alone (see 
                                          Table 7
                                       ). LDL-C reductions induced by ZETIA were generally consistent across all statins.

ZETIA co-administered with fenofibrate significantly lowered total-C, LDL-C, Apo B, and non-HDL-C compared to fenofibrate administered alone. The percent decrease in TG and percent increase in HDL-C for ZETIA co-administered with fenofibrate were comparable to those for fenofibrate administered alone (see 
                                    Table 12
                                 ).
